WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.220 --> 00:00:04.830
Isolated tribes live all over the planet,
humans who have NO IDEA what YouTube is, and

00:00:04.830 --> 00:00:07.450
have never seen an iPhone, or a metal knife.

00:00:07.450 --> 00:00:10.980
How come they're still out there?

00:00:10.980 --> 00:00:17.470
Hello everyone, Trace here reporting for DNews.

00:00:17.470 --> 00:00:22.339
In late June a previously isolated tribe in
Brazil walked out of the Amazon rainforest

00:00:22.339 --> 00:00:25.949
and peacefully approached a team of government
scientists.

00:00:25.949 --> 00:00:29.080
This was the first time in 20 years they'd
done so!

00:00:29.080 --> 00:00:33.590
The Brazilian Indian Affairs Department or
FUNAI, said it wasn't a normal approach and

00:00:33.590 --> 00:00:34.590
was worried.

00:00:34.590 --> 00:00:38.790
They believe illegal logging forced these
people from their ancestral homes.

00:00:38.790 --> 00:00:43.300
There are humans all over this planet who
still live like our ancient ancestors.

00:00:43.300 --> 00:00:47.280
There may be 100 different isolated groups
across the Amazon and New Guinea, on islands

00:00:47.280 --> 00:00:50.970
off the coast of India, and in Malaysia and
central Africa.

00:00:50.970 --> 00:00:55.490
Even the most isolated usually make contact
with OTHER tribes and some of those secondary

00:00:55.490 --> 00:00:57.980
tribes contact the local government regularly.

00:00:57.980 --> 00:01:01.871
Not to mention, anthropologists attempt to
photograph these people from the air, and

00:01:01.871 --> 00:01:05.830
missionaries attempt to evangelize on the
ground -- so even if they don't understand

00:01:05.830 --> 00:01:10.490
what that giant metal bird is, they know other
humans are around.

00:01:10.490 --> 00:01:13.970
The largest isolated tribal area on earth
is in South America.

00:01:13.970 --> 00:01:18.180
The Peruvian and Brazilian governments have
laws reserving land for these tribes to live

00:01:18.180 --> 00:01:19.180
on.

00:01:19.180 --> 00:01:23.210
Brazil used to forcibly assimilate tribes,
but now they have a policy of non-interference,

00:01:23.210 --> 00:01:25.060
similar to Star Trek's Prime Directive.

00:01:25.060 --> 00:01:30.010
Which sounds great on paper, but most reserves
end up being ravaged by illegal oil, logging,

00:01:30.010 --> 00:01:34.280
mining and drug-trafficking practices, driving
the tribes away or killing them.

00:01:34.280 --> 00:01:38.360
There are stories of tribes who fight back
being killed in all sorts of gruesome ways.

00:01:38.360 --> 00:01:45.600
Brazil has confirmed that 67 isolated tribes,
and Peru has 15 -- numbering more than 500

00:01:45.600 --> 00:01:46.600
people.

00:01:46.600 --> 00:01:50.190
The smallest known isolated tribe on our planet
is difficult to pinpoint.

00:01:50.190 --> 00:01:54.659
There are tribes of only a handful of individuals,
down to just one.

00:01:54.659 --> 00:01:59.590
A man in his 40s living in the Brazilian state
of RondÃ´nia (HONduonia) is the last survivor

00:01:59.590 --> 00:02:03.890
of his tribe, the rest likely being killed
by modern humans.

00:02:03.890 --> 00:02:06.190
No one knows his name or his lost tribe.

00:02:06.190 --> 00:02:07.390
